<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-713-299  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 713 299.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Dec 17 1990 v24 n51 p46(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>A personal computer sets out to sea. (Mississippi Department ofEconomic and Community Development supplies computer system thatdetermines where fish are most likely to be found)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Anthes, Gary H.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Mississippi Department of Economic and Community Developmentsupplies a microcomputer-based system with a map display thatindicates specific areas where fish are likely to be found and hasa water-temperature database that can be updated up to every 52minutes.andP;  The National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA)developed the software, which computes water-temperature contoursfrom satellite data; the National Marine Fisheries Servicecontributed features to display water depth and submergedobstacles.andP;  The state agency added rules that characterize thebehavior of 12 species of fish found in the Gulf of Mexico.andP;  Fourfishermen were selected to test the system, which works soeffectively that it has been criticized by environmental groupswho fear its use may lead to the depletion of less common fishspecies.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     System DevelopmentComputer SystemsInformation SystemsMississippi. Department of Economic and Community DevelopmentVertical MarketFishing Industry.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>